<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ui-lib-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>frontend-developer</domain>
    <summary>UI library patterns: compound components, accessible modals, and Storybook CSF 3 stories.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>react</tag>
      <tag>components</tag>
      <tag>ui-libraries</tag>
      <tag>storybook</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
    <frameworks>
      <framework>react</framework>
      <framework>storybook</framework>
    </frameworks>
    <languages>
      <language>typescript</language>
      <language>javascript</language>
    </languages>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>UI Library Advanced Patterns</title>
    <summary>Advanced patterns for UI libraries: compound components, accessible modal portals, and Storybook CSF 3 stories with testing. Ship primitives as 4-file units.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Compound components expose a self-documenting sub-component API (Card.Header, Card.Content) while sharing state through context without prop drilling. Modal portals must implement the WAI-ARIA dialog pattern precisely — agents routinely miss aria-modal, aria-labelledby, and focus return on close.</p>
      <p>Storybook CSF 3 stories with interaction testing enable agent-driven component generation with built-in verification. Without a clear pattern, each component emerges differently, creating maintenance burden and inconsistent tree-shaking behavior.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building compound components (Tabs, Accordion, Card) for an in-house UI library.</item>
        <item>Implementing accessible Modal/Dialog/Popover with portal, focus trap, ESC handling.</item>
        <item>Producing a Component.stories.tsx for every primitive in a Storybook-backed library.</item>
        <item>Migrating a one-off component into a reusable, typed library entry.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-off page UI that will never be reused — compound pattern adds context overhead with no payoff.</item>
        <item>Apps already using Radix UI or React Aria — wrap those instead of re-implementing dialog semantics.</item>
        <item>Server Components-only trees: compound components rely on React context, requiring 'use client'.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Compound Component Pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Create a context for shared state, a Root component that provides it, and sub-components that consume it. Export sub-components as both named exports and as Object.assign properties.</statement>
        <rationale>Object.assign-only export prevents tree-shaking; named exports let bundlers drop unused sub-components.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Card with Context and Multiple Export Styles">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
const CardContext = createContext<{ variant: 'default' | 'elevated' } | null>(null);

function useCardContext() {
  const ctx = useContext(CardContext);
  if (!ctx) throw new Error('Card sub-components must be used inside <Card>');
  return ctx;
}

function CardRoot({ children, variant = 'default', className }: CardProps) {
  return (
    <CardContext.Provider value={{ variant }}>
      <article className={clsx(styles.card, styles[variant], className)}>
        {children}
      </article>
    </CardContext.Provider>
  );
}

export function CardHeader({ children, className }: SubProps) {
  return <header className={clsx(styles.header, className)}>{children}</header>;
}

// Both forms: named export + Object.assign for ergonomic JSX
export const Card = Object.assign(CardRoot, { Header: CardHeader, Content: CardContent });
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Throw a descriptive error from useXContext() when used outside the Provider, not a silent null.</statement>
        <rationale>Silent nulls from missing context produce cryptic rendering failures; a thrown error with the component name lets the agent diagnose instantly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use data-state="open|closed" attributes instead of conditional class strings for state-driven styling.</statement>
        <rationale>Radix-style data attributes simplify both CSS selectors and test assertions; conditional class strings scatter state logic across the component.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Modal Portal and WAI-ARIA Dialog Pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every modal must set role="dialog", aria-modal="true", aria-labelledby pointing to the heading id, and optionally aria-describedby for the description.</statement>
        <rationale>Screen readers announce the dialog and its label on focus; missing attributes cause the dialog to be announced as a generic region with no context.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Modal with Complete ARIA Attributes">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
<div
  role="dialog"
  aria-modal="true"
  aria-labelledby="modal-title"
  aria-describedby={description ? 'modal-description' : undefined}
>
  <h2 id="modal-title">{title}</h2>
  {description && <p id="modal-description">{description}</p>}
</div>
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Gate createPortal behind a useEffect mount check. Never call createPortal during SSR — document.body does not exist on the server.</statement>
        <rationale>createPortal to document.body throws "document is not defined" during SSR/SSG without a mount guard.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="SSR-Safe Portal Rendering">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
useEffect(() => setMounted(true), []);
if (!isOpen || !mounted) return null;
return createPortal(<dialog>...</dialog>, document.body);
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Lock document.body scroll when the modal opens via useEffect. Remove the lock and keyboard listener in the cleanup function.</statement>
        <rationale>Without scroll lock, the page behind the overlay scrolls on touch devices. Without cleanup, the listener accumulates on repeated open/close cycles.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Scroll Lock and ESC Handler">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isOpen) return;
  document.body.style.overflow = 'hidden';
  const handler = (e: KeyboardEvent) => { if (e.key === 'Escape') onClose(); };
  document.addEventListener('keydown', handler);
  return () => {
    document.body.style.overflow = '';
    document.removeEventListener('keydown', handler);
  };
}, [isOpen, onClose]);
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="CSF 3 Storybook Story Conventions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use satisfies Meta&lt;typeof Component&gt; for meta and StoryObj&lt;typeof meta&gt; for story types. Always include tags: ['autodocs'] to generate a docs page.</statement>
        <rationale>Omitting tags: ['autodocs'] is the single most common reason a component has no autodocs page in Storybook 8.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="CSF 3 Shape with Type Safety">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from '@storybook/react';
import { fn } from '@storybook/test';
import { Button } from './Button';

const meta = {
  title: 'Primitives/Button',
  component: Button,
  tags: ['autodocs'],
  args: { onClick: fn() },
} satisfies Meta<typeof Button>;
export default meta;
type Story = StoryObj<typeof meta>;

export const Primary: Story = { args: { children: 'Primary', variant: 'primary' } };
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always await userEvent calls inside play functions. Assertions fire before React updates without await, producing flaky tests.</statement>
        <rationale>userEvent is async; without await the DOM state is stale when expect() runs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Async Play Function with User Interaction">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
export const ClickInteraction: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement, args }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await userEvent.click(canvas.getByRole('button'));
    await expect(args.onClick).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
  },
};
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Flaky Play Function Without Await">
        <code lang="tsx"><![CDATA[
// Missing await — assertion fires before click propagates
play: ({ canvasElement, args }) => {
  const canvas = within(canvasElement);
  userEvent.click(canvas.getByRole('button'));
  expect(args.onClick).toHaveBeenCalled(); // flaky
},
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use parameters: { controls: { exclude: [...] } } to hide inherited HTML attributes from the autodocs prop table.</statement>
        <rationale>Without filtering, every HTMLButtonAttribute appears in the controls panel, making the useful props invisible.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>Use Claude subagents to scaffold the entire 5-file methodology output (component, stories, tests, types, MDX docs) per primitive. Drive generation from a typed component spec (props table + variants + a11y requirements) so the agent has unambiguous input. Keep human review on every accessibility behavior (focus trap, aria-* wiring) — those are the load-bearing parts and the most common LLM regression points.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent (wrap the scaffold component → write stories → run a11y/visual tests → commit loop with quality gates), password-scrubber-agent (only relevant before publishing examples that quote real .env.local API keys; safe to skip otherwise).</p>
      <p>Prompt pattern: "Generate compound component for Tabs matching the Card pattern in ui-lib-patterns/methodology.xml. Required sub-components: Root, List, Trigger, Panel. Use Radix UI primitives under the hood. Output .tsx, .module.css, .stories.tsx, .test.tsx." / "Audit Modal.tsx against the WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices dialog pattern. Return a diff that fixes any gaps in focus trap, initial focus, return focus, and ESC handling."</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Tools and Services">
      <p>CLI tools: npx storybook@latest init (Bootstrap Storybook 8.x with framework auto-detect), npx shadcn-ui@latest add &lt;comp&gt; (Drop battle-tested compound components into the repo, then customize), pnpm dlx tsx scripts/gen-component.ts (Custom scaffolder for the 5-file pattern), npx playwright test --grep @a11y (Run @axe-core/playwright a11y suite against Storybook), npx chromatic --project-token=$CHROMATIC_TOKEN (Visual regression on every story).</p>
      <p>Services and apps: Chromatic (SaaS, Visual regression + Storybook hosting; agent commits and reads PR-status checks), Storybook (OSS, storybook dev, storybook build are scriptable; CSF stories are typed and easy for LLMs to write), Radix UI (OSS, Accept Radix as compound-component primitives — agents only style + compose), React Aria (Adobe, OSS, Hooks-based; LLMs misuse mergeProps. Pin examples in prompts.), Figma → Tokens Studio (SaaS, Sync design tokens into the lib; pair with style-dictionary).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Export sub-components as named exports too, not only via Object.assign, so consumers can tree-shake.</item>
        <item>Throw a descriptive error from useXContext() when the hook is used outside the Provider — agents otherwise produce confusing nulls.</item>
        <item>Use data-state="open|closed" instead of conditional class strings — Radix-style state attributes simplify CSS and tests.</item>
        <item>For every primitive ship: component + stories + a11y test + visual test. No "component-only" PRs.</item>
        <item>Keep the compound API additive — never remove a sub-component without a deprecation cycle; downstream apps will pin the import shape.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs frequently forget 'use client' on compound components in Next.js App Router → silent SSR mismatch.</item>
        <item>Generated Modal code often skips aria-modal="true" or wires aria-labelledby to a non-existent id; require an a11y test that asserts both.</item>
        <item>Agents tend to inline raw color hex values; force them to read from design-tokens-basics semantic tokens.</item>
        <item>When asked to "make it dynamic", agents add styled.div inside the render body — block this in review (see css-in-js-advanced perf section).</item>
        <item>Storybook 8 deprecated argTypesRegex for actions in some setups; pin the Storybook version in the prompt or the generator emits stale config.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.radix-ui.com/primitives"/>
      <link href="https://ui.shadcn.com"/>
      <link href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/"/>
      <link href="https://kentcdodds.com/blog/compound-components-with-react-hooks"/>
      <link href="https://storybook.js.org/docs/api/csf"/>
    </see-also>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/gen-compound.sh" purpose="Scaffolds compound component skeleton from name and sub-component list"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
